abstract= {The problem of stabilization of equilibria is one of the central issues in control.  In addition to its intrinsic interest, it represents a first step towards the solution of more complicated problems, such as the stabilization of periodic orbits or general invariant sets, or the attainment of other control objectives, such as tracking, disturbance rejection, or output feedback, all of which may be interpreted as requiring the stabilization of some quantity (typically, some sort of ``error'' signal).  A very special case, when there are no inputs, is that of stability.  This short and informal article provides an introduction to the subject.
